What systemd is, in one minute.

Systemd is the init system, process one, on every major modern linux distribution. It is also more than that: it is a whole suite of related daemons, including journal-d for logs, log-in-d for login sessions, network-d for networking, and resolved for dee-en-ess. But its core job is managing the system's services.

What does it actually do? It starts services in dependency order, running them in parallel wherever it can to speed up boot. It manages the whole lifecycle of a service, restarting it if it crashes, running it on a schedule, or activating it only when something needs it. It tracks each service's processes using the kernel's control groups, so that stopping a service reliably stops all of its child processes too, with none left orphaned. It gathers everyone's log output into a single journal. And it handles boot targets, which describe what ought to be running for, say, a graphical desktop versus a plain server.

Everything systemd manages is called a unit, and units are described by simple text files. Those files live in two main places, and the distinction matters. The vendor-supplied units, dropped in by the packages you install, live under slash lib or slash you-ess-are slash lib, and you should not edit them. Your own units, and your overrides of the vendor ones, live under slash e-t-c slash systemd slash system, which takes priority. The rule of thumb is simple: you read the existing units under slash lib, and you write your own new units and overrides under slash e-t-c.
